description:
This is the fish that shut down Atascadero Creek in 2013.  You can't see it in the photo, but it's hovering over its nest. 

Lisa Thompson (UC Davis) told me this about the sacred fish:

Rainbow trout and steelhead (trout) are the same species, Oncorhynchus mykiss.   The only difference is that steelhead migrate to the ocean, where food is generally more abundant, so when they return to freshwater to spawn they are larger than the "resident" rainbow trout who spend their whole life in freshwater.  The trade-off for the steelhead is that they have to brave the more dangerous ocean conditions, with larger predators, in order to gain the size and reproductive advantage.  The larger the female, the more eggs she produces.

Interestingly, steelhead mothers can produce rainbow trout offspring, and vice versa.  In southern California, where long droughts have occurred historically, this flexibility in life history probably helped the trout to survive.  If the creeks didn't flow enough to break through the lagoon sandbars for many years in a row, any steelhead out in the ocean would have died without reproducing, but the population could have been maintained by the resident rainbow trout in the creek headwaters (e.g., Rattlesnake Creek up above Mission Creek - the first place I saw southern steelhead trout). Once a good rain finally arrived, some of the rainbow trout offspring would have converted to being steelhead, migrated to the ocean, and returned to freshwater large and able to rapidly increase the population size.

In California the steelhead between Santa Cruz and Santa Maria are listed as threatened under the federal ESA, and between Santa Maria and the Mexico border they are listed as endangered.  There are steelhead as far south in California as Camp Pendleton, near Oceanside, and I've seen rainbow trout in the Tijuana River east of San Diego.  There are also a few isolated populations of trout in the highlands of Baja California, and east of the Gulf of California in Mexico.

description: a small fry approx 3 in. long.

The brook trout's body is elongate with an average length of 38.1-50.8 cm, is only slightly laterally compressed; the body has its greatest depth at or in front of the origin of the dorsal fin. Another physical characteristic of the brook trout is an adipose fin and a caudal fin that is slightly forked. The coloration of the brook trout is very distinct and can be spectacular. The back of the brook trout is dark olive-green to dark brown, sometimes almost black, the sides are lighter and become silvery white ventrally. On the back and top of the head there are wormy cream colored wavy lines known as vermiculations which break up into spots on the side. In addition to the pale spots on the side there are smaller more discrete red spots with bluish halos. The fins of the brook trout are also distinct; the dorsal fin has heavy black wavy lines, the caudal fin has black lines, the anal, pelvic and pectoral fins have white edges followed by black and then reddish coloration.

We've seen other fish trying to make it in their little dwindling pools, but this one was quite large for the size of the pool it was in. No dark speckles on body, faintly pink line on its side. Mouth all white inside.

The animal that was observed for this assignment was the Chinook Salmon, which was photographed at Bronte Creek National Park in Oakville, Ontario. The scientific name of the Chinook Salmon is Oncorhynchus tshawytscha, and has many common names including: King, Blackmouth, Quinnat, and Chub (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2013). 
	The Chinook Salmon has many different habitats. They start off in freshwater when they are born, migrate into the ocean as they are developing, and return as mature salmon to the rivers and streams where they were born to mate and reproduce (Scott, 2003). The freshwater streams are cold  around 14 degrees Celsius  and have fast flowing currents. These rivers are deep with coarse gravel found at the bottom (Scott, 2003). These salmon can also be found in estuaries, which provide the perfect transition zone from freshwater to salt water for developing salmon, in addition to being a great source of food and shelter (Scott, 2003). In the oceans, Chinook Salmon either stay close to shore, or migrate thousands of miles into the deep waters of the Pacific Ocean (Scott, 2003). The geographic range of these fish varies greatly. They are natively found in the Pacific Ocean. Their ranges span from Monterey Bay, California to the Chukchi Sea in Alaska, and from the Anadyr River in Siberia to Hokkaido, Japan (Scott, 2003). In addition to being found in these locations, they have also been introduced to numerous bodies of water around the world like those in New Zealand and the Great Lakes as a non-native species (Scott, 2003).  
	The Chinook Salmon is the largest of all the Pacific salmon species (Scott, 2003). The average weight of a Chinook Salmon is about 30 pounds (Scott, 2003).  Their average length is about 36 inches, growing a maximum of 58 inches long (Scott, 2003).  The lifespan of a Chinook Salmon is variable, with some salmon dying within their first year and others living 8 years or more (Scott, 2003).  The average age of mature adults is around 4-6 years in the wild (Scott, 2003). However, the average age of Chinook Salmon tend to depend on the location of their habitats. Those salmon that are situated more south have an average lifespan of about 2-4 years, while those salmon that have their habitats up north have average lifespans of about 5-7 years (Scott, 2003). Human impacts to the environment and habitats of the Chinook Salmon, like decreased water flow, increased siltation, and a decrease in oxygen availability, has played a role on their lifespan (Scott, 2003). The mortality rate of eggs and young salmon has increased due to these implications (Scott, 2003).  
	The diets of the Chinook Salmon vary depending on the age of the fish. Younger Chinook Salmon, 1 or 2 year olds, tend to eat the larvae and very young fish, as well as krill, crab and other micronekton in freshwater (Thayer, Field, & Sydeman, 2014). In ocean waters, the prey of the adult Chinook Salmon is different. They tend to feed on krill, crab, anchovies, herring, and squid, depending on which food is more abundant (Thayer, Field, & Sydeman, 2014). Also, we see Chinook Salmon feeding on Alewife, which is an overly abundant species of herring in the Great Lakes (Jacobs, Madenjian, Bunnell, Warner, & Claramunt, 2013). These salmon were brought into this area to control the booming population of Alewife (Jacobs, Madenjian, Bunnell, Warner, & Claramunt, 2013).
	During mating season, which is once a year, adult Chinook Salmon return to their birth streams (Scott, 2003).  The time of the year for breeding depends on the population of salmon, as well as the river; on average, Chinook Salmon tend to breed during the summer and autumn (Chinook Salmon, n.d). Sexual maturity is reached from ages 2-7, and soon after mating, they die (Scott, 2003). Reproduction occurs first with the female using her tail to dig a redds in the gravel of the river, which is the spawning nest for their eggs (Scott, 2003). The female deposits about 3,000-14,000 eggs, then the males deposit their sperm, and both parents guard the eggs until they die (Scott, 2003). The times at which the Chinook Salmon mate differ, like during the summer or autumn, but the younglings tend to hatch around the same time during the spring, where the vegetation is blossoming (Scott, 2003). In order for fertilization to occur, certain communication rituals must be completed by both the male and female Chinook Salmon (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000). While the females are busy building the redd for their eggs, the males are participating in a series of crosses and vibrations near the females (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000). Once the females are finished, they partake in intersexual selection  choosing their mate. Females tend to be more likely to choose the larger males that vibrate more than the males that are smaller and vibrate less (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000). Once the male is chosen, the female will go close to the male, and vibrate quickly to induce sperm release from the male (Berejikian, Tezak, & LaRae, 2000).	
	The Chinook Salmon have many predators, but they vary depending on whether these fish are young or adults. Young salmon have a higher mortality rate due to high predation because of their small size (Scott, 2003). Predators like striped bass, American shad, sculpins, and sea gulls like to feed on these small fish (Scott, 2003). When adult salmon return to their native rivers they are targeted by larger predators (Scott, 2003). Common predators include bears, killer whales, sea lions, seals, otters, and eagles (Scott, 2003). In coastal waters, killer whales are the top predators of these large salmon (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2013).
	Over the years, the population of the Chinook Salmon has been declining due to overfishing, climate change, damming, diverting water and habitat destruction (Scott, 2003). Damming blocks the salmon from returning to their birthplace, diverting water away from streams causes the river temperature to rise reducing the oxygen capacity, and habitat destruction takes away shelter for young salmon to use as protection from predators (Scott, 2003). The results of human actions are affecting this species of salmon, and are what is causing them to become endangered (Scott, 2003).
	Did you know that the world record for the heaviest Chinook Salmon is 127 pounds (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2013)?

description:
Need confirmation that this is the correct IDentification for this fish. Thanks.

--

2 August 2015: Observed a dead Bluegill Sunfish (Lepomis macrochirus) and what remained of the tail of a second on the bank of the Elm Fork Trinity River at the Lake Lewisville Evironmental Learning Area (LLELA) in Lewisville, Texas.

The Fish of the Elm Fork Trinity River 

At an online site called "Fishing Regulations for the Elm Fork Trinity River" the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department lists the various freshwater fish found in this river. These include the following: Black bass, white bass, striped bass, yellow bass, blue and channel catfish ("their hybrids and subspecies"), flathead catfish, carp, white and black crappie ("their hybrids and subspecies"), gar, alligator gar, brown trout, rainbow trout, and sunfish of which there are at least three named varieties in the river including bluegill, redear, and warmouth sunfish. That's at least 17 different named species of fish in the Elm Fork Trinity River and with "hybrids and subspecies" who knows the exact number. Still, the kind of fish represented by the one we photographed already dead on the river bank should be a bluegill. If anyone knows which one of the bluegills your IDentification of it would be appreciated, if not, we will just leave it be at Bluegill. To see this TPWD list of fish go to: https://tpwd.texas.gov/fishboat/fish/action/fishregs2.php?water=1195

tag_list: Largemouth Bass (Micropterus salmoides), Lewisville Lake Environmental Learning Area, Lewisville, Texas, fish, fall, bass, Elm Fork Trinity River, range, North America, native, United States, global distribution, Andrew Bridges and Cathleen Bester, "Largemouth Bass, " Icthyology, Biological Profiles, Florida Museum of Natural History
description:
Largemouth Bass (Micropterus salmoides)

31 October 2014: The water level in the Elm Fork Trinity River immediately downstream from the Lewisville Lake Dam's main water outlet at the Lewisville Lake Environmental Learning Area (LLELA) in Lewisville, Texas, was so low that the river's fish were being stranded on the sandbars along the course of the river. This was the case when we came upon this Largemouth Bass (Micropterus salmoides) that was stranded in mid-channel. We stopped up along the bank and the hiking trail and captured a few digital images of its predicament. The Largemouth Bass knew instinctively that it had to quickly get back into the river's stream in order to avoid becoming prey to one of the several large aquatic birds that frequent the site including egrets, cormorants, herons, and others. The river's bank at the spot where it was located was steep and impeded our intervening on its behalf and though the water level was low, almost trickling in places, the river bottom was ladened with moisture and had we stepped onto it our legs would likely be knee-deep in mud. Thus we left this nearly foot-long Largemouth Bass to its fate. It was trying desperately to move downstream and back into the river's flow. On this date we saw at least three other fish species in the river facing the same predicament as this Largemouth Bass.

Here is the thumbnail sketch presented at the Florida Natural History Museum's online review for Largemouth Bass under their Ichthyology section:

TAXONOMY

Lacpde was the first to describe this fish in 1802. He gave it the scientific name Labrus salmoides. In 1876, Nelson described this fish as Micropterus nigricans and in 1878 Jordan described it as Micropterus pallidus. Finally in 1884, Forbes described the fish as belonging to Micropterus salmoides, which is currently the valid scientific name.

There are two recognized subspecies the northern largemouth bass (Micropterus salmoides salmoides) and the Florida largemouth bass (Micropterus salmoides floridanus). In 1965, Smith described the subspecies Micropterus salmoides salmoides, while in 1949 Bailey and Hubbs described a second subspecies as Micropterus salmoides floridanus.

COMMON NAMES

Common names in the English language are largemouth bass, bass, American black bass, bayou bass, bigmouth bass, black bass, bucket mouth, chub, green bass, green trout, lake bass, large-mouth bass, largemouth, largemouth black bass, line side, marsh bass, northern largemouth bass, Oswego bass, slough bass, southern largemouth, trout, and welchman. Other common names include achiga (Portuguese), achigan (French), achigan  grande bouche (French), bas dehanbozorg (Persian), bass wielkgebowy (Polish), biban cu gura mare (Rumanian), black-bass  grande bouche (French), bol'sherotyi chernyi okun' (Russian), buraku basu (Japanese), fekete sgr (Hungarian), forelbaars (Dutch), forellenbarsch (German), huro (Spanish), isobassi (Finnish), khorshid mahi baleh kuchak (Persian), lakseabbor (Norwegian), lobina negra (Spanish), okounek pstruhov (Czech), Okuchibasu (Japanese), ostracka (Czech), ostracka lososovit (Slovak), perca americana (Spanish), perche d'amrique (French), perche noire (French), perche truite (French), perche truite (French), persico trota (Italian), stormundet black bass (Danish), stormundet rredaborre (Danish), tam suy lo ue (Cantonese), zwarte baars (Dutch), and ringabborre (Swedish).

GEOGRAPHICAL DISTRIBUTION

This bass is one of the most widely distributed fishes in the world. This is due in large part to the popularity of bass as a sport fish which has lead to the introduction of largemouth bass populations into many areas where they are not native. Their current range includes the U.S., South Africa, Europe, Guam, Japan, Lebanon, New Zealand, and the Philippines.

The original range of the largemouth bass is most of the eastern half of the United States, however it is now found generally in the majority of the United States, including swamps, ponds, lakes, reservoirs, creeks and large rivers.

--
Because it is a native species of North America, Largemouth Bass is most definitely an authentic resident of the Western Hemisphere. And because of its widespread distribution during the past century around the globe, it is most certainly a known resident of the world. LLELA is administered by a joint partnership consisting of the US Army Corps of Engineers, the City of Lewisville, Texas, the Lewisville Independent School District, and the University of North Texas.

Source: Andrew Bridges and Cathleen Bester, "Largemouth Bass," Icthyology, Biological Profiles, Florida Museum of Natural History, photographs, range map, description, accessed 1.16.16, http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/fish/gallery/descript/largemouthbass/largemouthbass.html

description:
There were two of the Small-mouth bass caught that day. Students could observe the fish caught and then the fish were released back into the pond. The larger bass, had a smaller fish in the inside of its mouth and what was visible when the mouth opened, was the fish tail on the roof of the bass' mouth. 
Small-mouth bass is known for having vertical stripes up the body, and a jaw that reaches half way through the eye. This species is the second largest member of the Centrarchidae family. The small-mouth bass is distinguished from the large mouth bass by the brown-green tinted scales. The smallmouth bass is native to the eastern coast of the United States and Canada. However, this specimen, and the others found in this lake were introduced by humans.

This is a black crappie. It was found in the pond behind the high school. The black crappie is a freshwater fish native to North America and is very similar to the white crappie in size, shape, and habits, except that it is darker with black spots. This crappie is assumed to be a younger fish because it has a black bar running through it's eye, which is not visible in mature black crappies. Also, they are also able to be distinguished from similar species by their seven to eight spines and dorsal fin.

Had to get some solo time this weekend, so I went to Lake Brownwood State Park.  The park ended up being pretty crowded, but fortunately, I was able to enjoy some nature by myself.  Temps were in the triple digits, and it was dry, dry, dry -- the plants needed a drink!

I sure enjoyed my time here as I hiked a few of the trails.
Six inches long.  Expired.

I caught one of the two bass that were spawning. They were a bed protecting their eggs in shallow water. It was around sundown so where the fish become more active since the sunlight is not as hot. Hot sunlight makes fish more lethargic. There were many bluegills attempting to eat the eggs. When I saw that there were many bluegills around it, I decided to fish with a live bluegill caught around the same area, on a waxworm. The bluegills would flee and run away, as the bass were more interested in protecting the future generation instead of feasting on bait fish. So then  I switched to a life like bluegill imitation lure that I could control myself. I positioned the lure on the specific spot that the eggs were on. The bass were very agitated by this so they swallowed the whole thing in. I then managed to bring this 16.5 in bass on the dock. This bass was safely returned to the bed so that they could reproduce.

description:
I parked my car at the convention center and hiked to Grace Creek.  The creek is at the bottom of a steep ravine and I had to do some exploring to find a way down.  I found a way in near the road, and right there was a deep hole containing fallen trees---perfect fish habitat.  The hole was a least five feet deep.  I know because I fell in while trying to retrieve my dropped sunglasses.  It's a good thing I didn't fall to the bottom, because I have no idea how deep it is.  I caught a couple of these guys before I fell.  Then I walked back to my car because I didn't want to get sick from standing around in cold, wet clothes.

I'm going to go back to this spot later this week.  Something bigger than a bluegill, like a bass or a catfish, is probably lurking in that hole.
